<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="In_film_and_television">In film and television</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><div id="mwe_player_0" class="PopUpMediaTransform" style="width:220px;" videopayload="&lt;div class=&quot;mediaContainer&quot; style=&quot;width:400px&quot;&gt;&lt;video id=&quot;mwe_player_1&quot; poster=&quot;//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv/400px--The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv.jpg&quot; controls=&quot;&quot; preload=&quot;none&quot; autoplay=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;width:400px;height:300px&quot; class=&quot;kskin&quot; data-durationhint=&quot;198.43176509843&quot; data-startoffset=&quot;0&quot; data-mwtitle=&quot;The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv&quot; data-mwprovider=&quot;wikimediacommons&quot;&gt;&lt;source src=&quot;//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d7/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv&quot; type=&quot;video/ogg; codecs=&amp;quot;theora&amp;quot;&quot; data-title=&quot;Original Ogg file, 400 × 300 (512 kbps)&quot; data-shorttitle=&quot;Ogg source&quot; data-width=&quot;400&quot; data-height=&quot;300&quot; data-bandwidth=&quot;512002&quot; data-framerate=&quot;29.97&quot;/&gt;&lt;source src=&quot;//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/d/d7/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv.120p.vp9.webm&quot; type=&quot;video/webm; codecs=&amp;quot;vp9, opus&amp;quot;&quot; data-title=&quot;Lowest bandwidth VP9 (120P)&quot; data-shorttitle=&quot;VP9 120P&quot; data-transcodekey=&quot;120p.vp9.webm&quot; data-width=&quot;160&quot; data-height=&quot;120&quot; data-bandwidth=&quot;107128&quot; data-framerate=&quot;29.97&quot;/&gt;&lt;source src=&quot;//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/d/d7/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv.160p.webm&quot; type=&quot;video/webm; codecs=&amp;quot;vp8, vorbis&amp;quot;&quot; data-title=&quot;Low bandwidth WebM (160P)&quot; data-shorttitle=&quot;WebM 160P&quot; data-transcodekey=&quot;160p.webm&quot; data-width=&quot;214&quot; data-height=&quot;160&quot; data-bandwidth=&quot;128032&quot; data-framerate=&quot;29.97&quot;/&gt;&lt;source src=&quot;//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/d/d7/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv.180p.vp9.webm&quot; type=&quot;video/webm; codecs=&amp;quot;vp9, opus&amp;quot;&quot; data-title=&quot;Low bandwidth VP9 (180P)&quot; data-shorttitle=&quot;VP9 180P&quot; data-transcodekey=&quot;180p.vp9.webm&quot; data-width=&quot;240&quot; data-height=&quot;180&quot; data-bandwidth=&quot;186736&quot; data-framerate=&quot;29.97&quot;/&gt;&lt;source src=&quot;//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/d/d7/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv.240p.webm&quot; type=&quot;video/webm; codecs=&amp;quot;vp8, vorbis&amp;quot;&quot; data-title=&quot;Small WebM (240P)&quot; data-shorttitle=&quot;WebM 240P&quot; data-transcodekey=&quot;240p.webm&quot; data-width=&quot;320&quot; data-height=&quot;240&quot; data-bandwidth=&quot;251720&quot; data-framerate=&quot;29.97&quot;/&gt;&lt;source src=&quot;//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/transcoded/d/d7/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv.240p.vp9.webm&quot; type=&quot;video/webm; codecs=&amp;quot;vp9, opus&amp;quot;&quot; data-title=&quot;Small VP9 (240P)&quot; data-shorttitle=&quot;VP9 240P&quot; data-transcodekey=&quot;240p.vp9.webm&quot; data-width=&quot;320&quot; data-height=&quot;240&quot; data-bandwidth=&quot;277752&quot; data-framerate=&quot;29.97&quot;/&gt;&lt;/video&gt;&lt;/div&gt;"><img alt="File:The Haunted Castle 1896.ogv" style="width:220px;height:165px" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d7/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv/220px--The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv.jpg" /><a href="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d7/The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv" title="Play media" target="new"><span class="play-btn-large"><span class="mw-tmh-playtext">Play media</span></span></a></div>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:The_Haunted_Castle_1896.ogv" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Haunted_Castle_(1896_film)" class="mw-redirect" title="The Haunted Castle (1896 film)">The Haunted Castle</a></i> (1896) (3:12)</div></div></div>
<p>The Devil is depicted as a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vampire_bat" title="Vampire bat">vampire bat</a> in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georges_M%C3%A9li%C3%A8s" title="Georges Méliès">Georges Méliès</a>' <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Haunted_Castle_(1896_film)" class="mw-redirect" title="The Haunted Castle (1896 film)">The Haunted Castle</a></i> (1896),<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPrince20041_276-0" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPrince20041-276">&#91;273&#93;</a></sup> which is often considered the first <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horror_film" title="Horror film">horror film</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDraven2010148_277-0" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDraven2010148-277">&#91;274&#93;</a></sup> So-called "Black Masses" have been portrayed in sensationalist <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B-movie" class="mw-redirect" title="B-movie">B-movies</a> since the 1960s.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllis2000157–158_278-0" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllis2000157–158-278">&#91;275&#93;</a></sup> One of the first films to portray such a ritual was the 1965 film <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eye_of_the_Devil" title="Eye of the Devil">Eye of the Devil</a></i>, also known as <i>13</i>. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alex_Sanders_(Wiccan)" title="Alex Sanders (Wiccan)">Alex Sanders</a>, a former black magician, served as a consultant on the film to ensure that the rituals portrayed in it were depicted accurately.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllis2000157_279-0" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllis2000157-279">&#91;276&#93;</a></sup> Over the next thirty years, the novels of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dennis_Wheatley" title="Dennis Wheatley">Dennis Wheatley</a> and the films of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hammer_Film_Productions" title="Hammer Film Productions">Hammer Film Productions</a> both played a major role in shaping the popular image of Satanism.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllis2000157–158_278-1" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllis2000157–158-278">&#91;275&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rosemary%27s_Baby_(film)" title="Rosemary&#39;s Baby (film)">film version</a> of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ira_Levin" title="Ira Levin">Ira Levin</a>'s <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rosemary%27s_Baby_(novel)" title="Rosemary&#39;s Baby (novel)">Rosemary's Baby</a></i> established made Satanic themes a staple of mainstream <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horror_fiction" title="Horror fiction">horror fiction</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllis2000159_280-0" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllis2000159-280">&#91;277&#93;</a></sup> Later films such as <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Exorcist_(film)" title="The Exorcist (film)">The Exorcist</a></i> (1973), <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Omen" title="The Omen">The Omen</a></i> (1976) and <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angel_Heart" title="Angel Heart">Angel Heart</a></i> (1987) feature Satan as an antagonist.<sup id="cite_ref-281" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-281">&#91;278&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="In_music">In music</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:262px;"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Le_Songe_de_Tartini_par_Louis-L%C3%A9opold_Boilly_1824.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Le_Songe_de_Tartini_par_Louis-L%C3%A9opold_Boilly_1824.jpg/260px-Le_Songe_de_Tartini_par_Louis-L%C3%A9opold_Boilly_1824.jpg" decoding="async" width="260" height="173" class="thumbimage" srcset="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Le_Songe_de_Tartini_par_Louis-L%C3%A9opold_Boilly_1824.jpg/390px-Le_Songe_de_Tartini_par_Louis-L%C3%A9opold_Boilly_1824.jpg 1.5x, https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/89/Le_Songe_de_Tartini_par_Louis-L%C3%A9opold_Boilly_1824.jpg/520px-Le_Songe_de_Tartini_par_Louis-L%C3%A9opold_Boilly_1824.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1117" data-file-height="744" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Le_Songe_de_Tartini_par_Louis-L%C3%A9opold_Boilly_1824.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><i>Tartini's Dream</i> (1824) by <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louis-L%C3%A9opold_Boilly" title="Louis-Léopold Boilly">Louis-Léopold Boilly</a></div></div></div>
<p>References to Satan in music can be dated back to the Middle Ages. During the fifth century, a musical interval called the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tritone" title="Tritone">tritone</a> became known as "the devil in Music" and was banned by the Catholic Church.<sup id="cite_ref-crack_282-0" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-crack-282">&#91;279&#93;</a></sup> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giuseppe_Tartini" title="Giuseppe Tartini">Giuseppe Tartini</a> was inspired to write his most famous work, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Violin_Sonata_in_G_minor_(Tartini)" title="Violin Sonata in G minor (Tartini)">Violin Sonata in G minor</a>, also known as "The Devil's Trill", after dreaming of the Devil playing the violin. Tartini claimed that the sonata was a lesser imitation of what the Devil had played in his dream.<sup id="cite_ref-283" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-283">&#91;280&#93;</a></sup> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niccol%C3%B2_Paganini" title="Niccolò Paganini">Niccolò Paganini</a> was believed to have derived his musical talent from a deal with the Devil.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESpignesi2003281_284-0" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-FOOTNOTESpignesi2003281-284">&#91;281&#93;</a></sup> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Gounod" title="Charles Gounod">Charles Gounod</a>'s <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faust_(opera)" title="Faust (opera)">Faust</a></i> features a narrative that involves Satan.<sup id="cite_ref-crack_282-1" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-crack-282">&#91;279&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the early 1900s, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jazz" title="Jazz">jazz</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blues" title="Blues">blues</a> became known as the "Devil's Music" as they were considered "dangerous and unholy".<sup id="cite_ref-crack_282-2" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-crack-282">&#91;279&#93;</a></sup> According to legend, blues musician <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Johnson_(musician)" title="Tommy Johnson (musician)">Tommy Johnson</a> was a terrible guitarist before exchanging his soul to the Devil for a guitar. Later, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Johnson" title="Robert Johnson">Robert Johnson</a> claimed that he had sold his soul in return for becoming a great blues guitarist.<sup id="cite_ref-285" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-285">&#91;282&#93;</a></sup> Satanic symbolism appears in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rock_music" title="Rock music">rock music</a> from the 1960s. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mick_Jagger" title="Mick Jagger">Mick Jagger</a> assumes the role of Lucifer in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Rolling_Stones" title="The Rolling Stones">the Rolling Stones</a>' "<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sympathy_for_the_Devil" title="Sympathy for the Devil">Sympathy for the Devil</a>" (1968),<sup id="cite_ref-crack_282-3" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-crack-282">&#91;279&#93;</a></sup> while <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Sabbath" title="Black Sabbath">Black Sabbath</a> portrayed the Devil in numerous songs, including "<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_Pigs" title="War Pigs">War Pigs</a>" (1970) and "<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N.I.B." title="N.I.B.">N.I.B.</a>" (1970).<sup id="cite_ref-286" class="reference"><a href="Satan#cite_note-286">&#91;283&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
